  "questionId": "gfg-sub-aptitude-line-graph",
  "title": "Line Graph",
  "content": {
    "problemStatement": "<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Line graph also known as a</span><b><strong> line chart </strong></b><span>or </span><b><strong>line plot</strong></b><span> is a tool used for </span><b><strong>data visualization</strong></b><span> . It is a type of graph that r</span><b><strong>epresents the data in a pictorial form </strong></b><span>which makes the raw data more easily understandable. In a line graph data points are connected with a straight-line and data points are represented either with points or wedges. Some other examples of graphs are </span><a href=\"#/articles/course/AptitudeCourses/gfg-sub-aptitude/maths/bar-graphs/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><b><strong>bar graphs</strong></b></a><b><strong>, </strong></b><a href=\"#/articles/course/AptitudeCourses/gfg-sub-aptitude/maths/histogram/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><b><strong>histograms</strong></b></a><b><strong>, </strong></b><a href=\"#/articles/course/AptitudeCourses/gfg-sub-aptitude/maths/pie-charts/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><b><strong>pie charts</strong></b></a><b><strong>, line graphs,</strong></b><span> etc. </span></p><blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>A </span><b><strong>line graph or line chart </strong></b><span>is a graphical representation of the data that displays the relationship between two or more variables concerning time. It is made by connecting data points with straight-line segments.</span></p></blockquote><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184024/Line-Graph-10-min.png\" alt=\"Image showing Parts of Line Graph\" width=\"827\" height=\"inherit\" srcset=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184024/Line-Graph-10-min.png 827w, https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184024/Line-Graph-10-min-100.png 100w, https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184024/Line-Graph-10-min-200.png 200w, https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184024/Line-Graph-10-min-300.png 300w, https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184024/Line-Graph-10-min-660.png 660w, https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184024/Line-Graph-10-min-768.png 768w, \"><figcaption>Line Graph</figcaption></figure><h2><span>Parts of Line Graph</span></h2><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Parts of the line graph include the following:</span></p><ul><li value=\"1\"><b><strong>Title:</strong></b><span> It is nothing but the title of the graph drawn.</span></li><li value=\"2\"><a href=\"#/articles/course/AptitudeCourses/gfg-sub-aptitude/maths/coordinate-axes/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><b><strong>Axes:</strong></b></a><span> The line graph contains two axes i.e. X-axis and Y-axis.</span></li><li value=\"3\"><b><strong>Labels:</strong></b><span> The name given to the x-axis and y-axis.</span></li><li value=\"4\"><b><strong>Line:</strong></b><span> It is the </span><a href=\"#/articles/course/AptitudeCourses/gfg-sub-aptitude/maths/line-segment/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><span>line segment</span></a><span> that is used to connect two or more data points.</span></li><li value=\"5\"><b><strong>Point:</strong></b><span> It is nothing but a point given at each segment.</span></li></ul><blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\"><b><strong>Learn more about </strong></b><a href=\"#/articles/course/AptitudeCourses/gfg-sub-aptitude/maths/points-lines-and-planes/\" rel=\"noopener\"><b><strong>Point, Lines, and Plane</strong></b></a><b><strong>.</strong></b></p></blockquote><h2 id=\"how-to-make-a-line-graph\"><span>How to Draw and Read a Line Graph?</span></h2><h3 id=\"drawing-a-line-graph\"><span>Drawing a line Graph</span></h3><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>To make a line graph we need to use the following steps:</span></p><blockquote><ol><li value=\"1\"><b><strong>Determine the variables: </strong></b><span>The first and foremost step is to identify the variables you want to plot on the X-axis and Y-axis.</span></li><li value=\"2\"><b><strong>Choose appropriate scales: </strong></b><span>Based on your data, determine the appropriate scale.</span></li><li value=\"3\"><b><strong>Plot the points:</strong></b><span> Plot the individual data points on the graph according to the given data.</span></li><li value=\"4\"><b><strong>Connect the points:</strong></b><span> After plotting the points, you have to connect those points with a line.</span></li><li value=\"5\"><b><strong>Label the axes:</strong></b><span> Add labels to the X-axis and Y-axis. You can also include the unit of measurement.</span></li><li value=\"6\"><b><strong>Add Title:</strong></b><span> After completing the graph you should provide a suitable title.</span></li></ol></blockquote><h3 id=\"reading-a-line-graph\"><b><strong>Reading a Line Graph</strong></b></h3><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>To read a line graph you need to follow the below given steps:</span></p><blockquote><ol><li value=\"1\"><b><strong>Understand the axes:</strong></b><span> First, you need to understand the X-axis and Y-axis of the graph.</span></li><li value=\"2\"><b><strong>Estimate the scale: </strong></b><span>Look at the values marked along each axis to determine the scale.</span></li><li value=\"3\"><b><strong>Estimate the values of data points: </strong></b><span>Look at the data points on the graph to estimate the values on the graph.</span></li><li value=\"4\"><b><strong>Analyze the pattern:</strong></b><span> Identify the pattern and analyze it.</span></li><li value=\"5\"><b><strong>Conclude: </strong></b><span>Based on the above step find conclusions.</span></li></ol></blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\"><b><strong>Example: Draw a line graph for the given data</strong></b></p><table><thead></thead><tbody><tr><th><span>No. of Days</span></th><td><b><strong>1</strong></b></td><td><b><strong>2</strong></b></td><td><b><strong>3</strong></b></td><td><b><strong>4</strong></b></td></tr><tr><th><span>Absentees</span></th><td><b><strong>5</strong></b></td><td><b><strong>10</strong></b></td><td><b><strong>15</strong></b></td><td><b><strong>10</strong></b></td></tr></tbody></table><p dir=\"ltr\"><b><strong>Answer:</strong></b></p><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184026/Line-Graph-08-min.png\" alt=\"Example of Line Graph\" width=\"827\" height=\"inherit\" srcset=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184026/Line-Graph-08-min.png 827w, https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184026/Line-Graph-08-min-100.png 100w, https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184026/Line-Graph-08-min-200.png 200w, https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184026/Line-Graph-08-min-300.png 300w, https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184026/Line-Graph-08-min-660.png 660w, https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184026/Line-Graph-08-min-768.png 768w, \" loading=\"lazy\"><figcaption>Line Graph between Days and No. of Absentees</figcaption></figure><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>The above diagram shows a line graph between No. of days and the number of absentees.</span></p><h2 id=\"types-of-line-graph\"><span>Types of Line Graph</span></h2><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Let us discuss the types of line graphs:</span></p><ul><li value=\"1\"><b><strong>Simple Line Graph</strong></b></li><li value=\"2\"><b><strong>Multiple Line Graph</strong></b></li><li value=\"3\"><b><strong>Compound Line Graph</strong></b></li></ul><h3 id=\"simple-line-graph\"><b><strong>Simple Line Graph</strong></b></h3><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>It is the most common type of line graph in which a single line represents the relationship between two variables over time. The above diagram is an example of a basic line graph.</span></p><h3 id=\"multiple-line-graph\"><b><strong>Multiple Line Graph</strong></b></h3><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>It is the type of line graph in which we can represent two or more lines in a single graph and they can either belong to the same categories or different which makes it easy to make comparisons between them. Multiple line graphs also include a double line graph or we can say that a double line graph is also a multiple line graph.</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>An example of multiple graphs is shown below:</span></p><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184029/Line-Graph-03-min.png\" alt=\"Multiple Line Graph\" width=\"827\" height=\"inherit\" srcset=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184029/Line-Graph-03-min.png 827w, https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184029/Line-Graph-03-min-100.png 100w, https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184029/Line-Graph-03-min-200.png 200w, https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184029/Line-Graph-03-min-300.png 300w, https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184029/Line-Graph-03-min-660.png 660w, https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184029/Line-Graph-03-min-768.png 768w, \" loading=\"lazy\"><figcaption>Line Graph between Quantity and Year</figcaption></figure><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>In the above graph sale of product A and B is shown in the same graph.</span></p><h3 id=\"compound-line-graph\"><b><strong>Compound Line Graph</strong></b></h3><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>It is a type of line graph in which multiple lines or data are combined into a single graph showing different categories or variables. The main aim of a compound line graph is to represent or display the relationship between different variables on a single graph.</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>A Compound Line graph example is shown below:</span></p><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184023/Line-Graph-77-min.png\" alt=\"Compound Line Graph\" width=\"826\" height=\"inherit\" srcset=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184023/Line-Graph-77-min.png 826w, https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184023/Line-Graph-77-min-100.png 100w, https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184023/Line-Graph-77-min-200.png 200w, https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184023/Line-Graph-77-min-300.png 300w, https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184023/Line-Graph-77-min-660.png 660w, https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184023/Line-Graph-77-min-768.png 768w, \" loading=\"lazy\"><figcaption>Line Graph between Time and No. Of Vehicles</figcaption></figure><h2 id=\"advantages-of-line-graph\"><span>Advantages of Line Graph</span></h2><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Some of the advantages of using line graph are listed below:</span></p><ul><li value=\"1\"><span>It helps to visualize the data.</span></li><li value=\"2\"><span>It provides a clear overview of the data.</span></li><li value=\"3\"><span>It becomes easy to make predictions using a line graph.</span></li><li value=\"4\"><span>It helps to compare the data more easily.</span></li></ul><p dir=\"ltr\"><b><strong>Note</strong></b><span>: Line graph is not suitable to show non linear relationship or complex data </span></p><blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\"><b><strong>Articles related to Line Graph:</strong></b></p><ul><li value=\"1\"><a href=\"#/articles/course/AptitudeCourses/gfg-sub-aptitude/maths/statistics/\" rel=\"noopener\"><b><strong>Statistics</strong></b></a></li><li value=\"2\"><a href=\"#/articles/course/AptitudeCourses/gfg-sub-aptitude/maths/bar-graphs-and-histograms/#:~:text=relationships%20among%20data.-,Bar%20Graph,-The%20pictorial%20representation\" rel=\"noopener\"><b><strong>Bar Graphs</strong></b></a></li><li value=\"3\"><a href=\"#/articles/course/AptitudeCourses/gfg-sub-aptitude/maths/bar-graphs-and-histograms/#:~:text=the%20x-axis.-,Histograms,-Histograms%20are%20the\" rel=\"noopener\"><b><strong>Histograms</strong></b></a></li><li value=\"4\"><a href=\"#/articles/course/AptitudeCourses/gfg-sub-aptitude/maths/pie-charts/\" rel=\"noopener\"><b><strong>Pie Chart</strong></b></a></li></ul></blockquote><h2 id=\"solved-problems-on-line-graph\"><span>Solved Examples on Line Graph</span></h2><p dir=\"ltr\"><b><strong>Examples 1: Draw a line graph for the given data.</strong></b></p><table><thead></thead><tbody><tr><th><span>Time</span></th><td><span>6 AM</span></td><td><span>10 AM</span></td><td><span>2 PM</span></td><td><span>6 PM</span></td></tr><tr><th><span>Temperature (in </span><sup><span>o</span></sup><span>C)</span></th><td><span>35</span></td><td><span>45</span></td><td><span>50</span></td><td><span>40</span></td></tr></tbody></table><p dir=\"ltr\"><b><strong>Solution:</strong></b></p><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184028/Line-Graph-05-min.png\" alt=\"Temperature vs time Line Graph\" width=\"827\" height=\"inherit\" srcset=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184028/Line-Graph-05-min.png 827w, https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184028/Line-Graph-05-min-100.png 100w, https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184028/Line-Graph-05-min-200.png 200w, https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184028/Line-Graph-05-min-300.png 300w, https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184028/Line-Graph-05-min-660.png 660w, https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184028/Line-Graph-05-min-768.png 768w, \" loading=\"lazy\"><figcaption>Line Graph: Temperature vs Time </figcaption></figure><p dir=\"ltr\"><br><b><strong>Examples 2: Draw a line graph from the given data and answer the following questions.</strong></b></p><table><thead></thead><tbody><tr><th><span>Product A</span></th><td><span>150</span></td><td><span>125</span></td><td><span>100</span></td><td><span>50</span></td></tr><tr><th><span>Product B</span></th><td><span>125</span></td><td><span>150</span></td><td><span>50</span></td><td><span>100</span></td></tr></tbody></table><p dir=\"ltr\"><b><strong>(a) In the above graph find in which year the sale of product A is maximum.</strong></b></p><p dir=\"ltr\"><b><strong>(b)</strong></b><span> </span><b><strong>Find in which year the sale of product B is the minimum.</strong></b></p><p dir=\"ltr\"><b><strong>(c) Find in which year the sale of products A and B is the same.</strong></b></p><p dir=\"ltr\"><b><strong>Solution:</strong></b></p><blockquote><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184027/Line-Graph-06-min.png\" alt=\"Line Graph showing sale of Product A and B over the years\" width=\"827\" height=\"inherit\" srcset=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184027/Line-Graph-06-min.png 827w, https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184027/Line-Graph-06-min-100.png 100w, https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184027/Line-Graph-06-min-200.png 200w, https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184027/Line-Graph-06-min-300.png 300w, https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184027/Line-Graph-06-min-660.png 660w, https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184027/Line-Graph-06-min-768.png 768w, \" loading=\"lazy\"><figcaption>Line Graph for Sale of Product A and B over the years</figcaption></figure><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>(a) In 2011, the sale of product A is maximum.</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>(b) In 2013, the sale of Product B is minimum.</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>(c) There is no year in which the sale of Product A and B is the same.</span></p></blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\"><b><strong>Examples 3: Draw a compound line graph for the given data.</strong></b></p><table><thead><tr><th><span>&nbsp;</span></th><th><span>Samsung</span></th><th><span>Apple</span></th><th><span>One Plus</span></th><th><span>Vivo</span></th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><th><span>Quarter 1</span></th><td><span>7</span></td><td><span>12</span></td><td><span>9</span></td><td><span>17</span></td></tr><tr><th><span>Quarter 2</span></th><td><span>32</span></td><td><span>21</span></td><td><span>20</span></td><td><span>25</span></td></tr><tr><th><span>Quarter 3</span></th><td><span>52</span></td><td><span>60</span></td><td><span>65</span></td><td><span>70</span></td></tr></tbody></table><p dir=\"ltr\"><b><strong>Solution:</strong></b></p><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184025/Line-Graph-09-min.png\" alt=\"Line Graph showing Sale of Mobile Phones over each Quarter\" width=\"750\" height=\"inherit\" srcset=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184025/Line-Graph-09-min.png 750w, https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184025/Line-Graph-09-min-100.png 100w, https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184025/Line-Graph-09-min-200.png 200w, https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184025/Line-Graph-09-min-300.png 300w, https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184025/Line-Graph-09-min-660.png 660w, \" loading=\"lazy\"><figcaption>Line Graph representing number of Mobile Phones sold in each Quarters </figcaption></figure><p dir=\"ltr\"><b><strong>Examples 4: Draw a line graph for the given data</strong></b></p><table><thead></thead><tbody><tr><th><span>Distance</span></th><td><span>20</span></td><td><span>30</span></td><td><span>35</span></td><td><span>45</span></td></tr><tr><th><span>Time</span></th><td><span>5</span></td><td><span>10</span></td><td><span>15</span></td><td><span>20</span></td></tr></tbody></table><p dir=\"ltr\"><b><strong>Solution:</strong></b></p><img src=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184028/Line-Graph-04-min.png\" alt=\"Distance vs Time Line Graph \" width=\"827\" height=\"inherit\" srcset=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184028/Line-Graph-04-min.png 827w, https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184028/Line-Graph-04-min-100.png 100w, https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184028/Line-Graph-04-min-200.png 200w, https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184028/Line-Graph-04-min-300.png 300w, https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184028/Line-Graph-04-min-660.png 660w, https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184028/Line-Graph-04-min-768.png 768w, \" loading=\"lazy\"><p dir=\"ltr\"><b><strong>Examples 5: Draw a line graph for the given data.</strong></b></p><table><thead></thead><tbody><tr><th><span>Input</span></th><td><span>1</span></td><td><span>2</span></td><td><span>4</span></td><td><span>5</span></td><td><span>7</span></td></tr><tr><th><span>Output</span></th><td><span>2</span></td><td><span>5</span></td><td><span>11</span></td><td><span>14</span></td><td><span>20</span></td></tr></tbody></table><p dir=\"ltr\"><b><strong>Solution:</strong></b></p><img src=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184030/Line-Graph-01-min.png\" alt=\"Line Graph Examples 05\" width=\"827\" height=\"inherit\" srcset=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184030/Line-Graph-01-min.png 827w, https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184030/Line-Graph-01-min-100.png 100w, https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184030/Line-Graph-01-min-200.png 200w, https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184030/Line-Graph-01-min-300.png 300w, https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184030/Line-Graph-01-min-660.png 660w, https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230727184030/Line-Graph-01-min-768.png 768w, \" loading=\"lazy\">",
